Report on the results of the parallel assessment of the Czech Republic and Germany's VAT administration
Preliminary remarks
The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, emphasises that the Courts of Auditors have the power to audit the entire public finances.
The declaration requires that the Courts of Auditors must have the power to assess tax collection as far as possible.
The Organisation of European Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) regards taxation as an important component of public revenue.
The thematic focus of the VI EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the audit of public revenue by the Courts of Auditors.
One of the most significant steps towards optimising the audit work of a Court of Auditors is the development of a specific strategy for public revenue audit.
This is particularly true of taxation as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.
As national economies are increasingly interconnected and interdependent, a situation may arise in which national audit firms can only carry out their audit work in cooperation with the audit firms of other countries.
An example can be the examination of internationally organised fraud, which can lead to significant loss of revenue in many countries.
Cooperation between authorities is needed in the fight against such crimes.
Auditing bodies in this area must be ready to work closely together.
The idea of an audit of VAT and the MIAS system was developed at the VI EUROSAI Congress in Bonn, which was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Court of Auditors.
In the course of thorough preparation, the participating courts first had to familiarise themselves with the legal framework and procedures of VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.
On the basis of the analysis of the available information, we selected the audit subject matter for the audit plan.
Achieving the efficient and effective management of VAT is a long-standing problem and individual Member States (in particular EC Member States) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of VAT and increase transparency in this area. dictate:
We are convinced that the results of our audit can not only contribute to improving the work of the financial administration, but also provide the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.
Report on the results of the parallel assessment of the Czech Republic and Germany's VAT administration
Introduction
Reference number: CZ) 06 / 27 (de) VIII 2 – 2005 – 1215
Subject-matter of the examination:
 (CZ) VAT administration after the Czech Republic's accession to the European Union
 (De) Examination of administrative cooperation in the field of VAT in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and 1925 / 2004
The Commission's audit objective is to:
 (CZ) The purpose of the audit in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures applied by the financial administration in the field of VAT following the integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (hereinafter referred to as "EC") with free movement of goods and services, as well as the the MIAS1, in particular the control of the use of the VAT exemption for intra-Community supplies.
 (De) The purpose of the audit was to examine the system of intra-Community VAT control with a focus on mutual assistance in the field of VAT in accordance with the above-mentioned regulations.
As a result of the examination, weaknesses should be identified and recommendations should be made to address them.
VAT Information Exchange System The audits were carried out jointly by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic ("NKÚ") and the Federal Court of Auditors ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany on the basis of an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006.
The cooperation focused on the review of selected transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the use of information obtained through international mutual assistance between the financial administrations and the comparison of VAT administration systems in both countries. dates.
A joint final report on the results of the audits has been prepared within the meaning of European guideline 31 for the implementation of INTOSAI audit standards.
The period examined covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.
Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel examination
The parallel audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two Courts of Auditors.
In addition to the focus on "exchange of information" under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925 / 2004, other closely related aspects, such as registration of taxable persons, tax returns and summary reports, were also examined.
The audit also covered the legal situation of cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach and the comparison of statistical data.
The comparison of VAT administration systems in the two Member States revealed differences in the following areas:
1) Registration for VAT purposes.
While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the level of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among others, the main criterion for registration is to exceed the turnover threshold laid down in the VAT Act.
In the Czech Republic, taxable persons receive only one tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, for the purposes of VAT, the taxable person receives a tax number only applicable to domestic transactions.
If the German taxpayer wishes to make intra-Community transactions, he must apply for a special identification number, the so-called VAT number.
Given the difficulties arising from the different registration procedures, the rules should be harmonised within the EC (see 4.1).
2) Cross-border passenger transport by bus.
In the Czech Republic, the international carriage of passengers by coach is exempt from VAT, but there is a right to deduct the VAT.
In Germany, as far as the route passes through Germany, the carriage is subject to VAT.
Efforts should be made at EC level to harmonise the situation under Article 393 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of value added tax (see 4.2).
3) Tax declarations.
Whereas in the Czech Republic taxable persons have to issue VAT returns only for sub-year tax periods (month or quarter), taxable persons have to issue VAT returns in Germany (monthly or quarterly) 
Submit VAT pre-notifications and an annual VAT declaration after the end of the calendar year.
Unlike the Czech Republic, taxpayers in Germany are required to submit VAT pre-notifications by electronic means.
The introduction of compulsory electronic VAT returns in the Czech Republic would improve the efficiency of the Czech financial administration (see 4.3).
4) Summary notifications.
While taxpayers in the Czech Republic have to submit their summary reports to the financial offices (Fä), German taxpayers have to submit the summary reports to the ClO2.
Accordingly, the information from the summary notifications will be available to the Fä in the Czech Republic immediately after they have been submitted.
The information contained in the summary notices would only be available to Germans after processing it by the CLO.
In order to combat VAT fraud, updated information on intra-Community transactions is needed as soon as possible.
The monthly submission of summary reports would shorten the period between the date of turnover and the update of the mias data.
This would allow a timely assessment of taxation in the acquirer's Member State (see 4.4), but only if all EC Member States introduced the same deadlines.
5) International exchange of information in the field of VAT.
In case of in-depth requests, the Czech CLO will monitor compliance with the three-month deadline.
The German CLO does not monitor processing times.
As a consequence, the German financial administration has completed a significantly lower percentage of requests for information received within the prescribed period.
Because of these problems, the BRH recommended that the German CLO continuously monitor the deadlines (see 4.6).
6) Risk management.
Each of the two Member States must develop its own risk management system (RMS) with appropriate strengths and weaknesses.
The Sao and the BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by a Member State alone.
Successful criteria, elements or approaches of an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in all EC Member States; otherwise, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5).
In the framework of the cooperation, the two courts examined selected cases of intra-Community transactions carried out between Czech and German tax entities.
Of these, 31 cases were examined jointly by exploiting the legal possibilities of the CLO, where there were doubts about the correct taxation or suspicion of VAT fraud.
The Courts of Auditors noted that:
In some cases, the information obtained in the international exchange of information was used to re-establish the VAT liability of the taxable persons concerned.
In those cases, the taxable persons had either unlawfully claimed the exemption from VAT or had not indicated the purchase of goods in their declaration of VAT.
In some cases, the information obtained in the exchange of information could not be used because it was incomplete or incomprehensible.
In other cases, the information could not be used because of different legislative provisions in the two Member States.
In some cases, the financial management of another Member State refused the requested information.
Some cases have been identified where taxable persons have not correctly declared transactions in their summary reports.
As a result, the data in the MIAS were correspondingly incorrect, so that the experts (the fä) had to identify in these cases (see 6).
