Registration of taxable persons in Germany
In accordance with the provisions of the order of duties (§ § 137, 138 AO), each operation must be notified to the municipality and / or the competent tax authority.
This notification shall be made no later than one month after the start of the business.
The municipality shall forward the notification to the tax authorities.
If the competent tax authority finds that a transaction has started but has not been notified, it may also register retroactively the taxpayer on its own initiative.
In Germany, taxable persons, whether they are resident or not, are required to register for VAT purposes if they fulfil the conditions set out in § 2 of the German VAT Act.
This does not depend on the level of turnover achieved.
There is no voluntary registration in Germany.
Entrepreneurs established abroad are particularly responsible for the fä.
For example, the Fa ChemnitzSüd is responsible for those entrepreneurs who have their headquarters in the Czech Republic.
A total of 295 Czech entrepreneurs were registered as of 30 April 2004 and 1,050 Czech entrepreneurs were registered as of 1 March 2006.
According to the BRH, these would often refuse, with special responsibilities, to register so-called "pseudo self-employed workers" residing in the new Central and Eastern European Member States of the EC.
Since the free movement of workers is still restricted after the accession of these ten countries to the EC, these self-employed attempted to circumvent these restrictions by establishing their own business.
These (apparent) self-employed workers do not fulfil the conditions for recognition as entrepreneurs laid down in Paragraph 2 of the UstG, since they are generally dependent on a single contracting authority which determines their working time and the type of work performed.
To be registered, the entrepreneur must complete a questionnaire of the relevant Fa and provide information on the undertaking and the activities carried out.
The questionnaire is a mandatory form for all Fä in Germany.
It shall be processed either in special organisational units within the Fä or in the organisational units generally responsible for tax investment.
This form will be used to carry out a risk assessment for the individual taxpayer prior to the allocation of a tax number.
The establishment of the tax number for domestic transactions is based on certain specifications:
The first three paragraphs are the identification number of the competent Fa, the following three (or four) paragraphs indicate which department is competent within the Fa, the following five (or four) paragraphs are the identification feature of the taxpayer: the last paragraph is always a check digit.
If an entrepreneur wants to participate in intra-Community trade, he needs a VAT number in order to be able to operate tax-free intra-Community supplies.
It is allocated by the CLO on request when the trader is registered in Germany for VAT purposes.
The VAT number is automatically allocated by the CLO when the taxable person declares intra-Community supplies in his VAT advance notices or in his VAT Annual Statement.
The VAT number consists of the country code (de) and a sequence of nine paragraphs.
The registration of an entrepreneur may be deleted: 1. on request (e.g. when he ceases business), but only after all tax operations have been completed (estimating all financial years) or 2. that he no longer operates.
As a rule, the validity of the VAT ID depends on the validity of the VAT number.
In such cases, the Fä must inform the CLO of the removal of the VAT number so that the VAT number can be terminated at that time.
According to the VAT Act (§ 19 (1) of the German VAT Act), domestic taxable persons are not required to pay a VAT in the following cases: 1. the turnover of the previous calendar year plus the VAT resulting therefrom did not exceed the amount of €17,500 and 2. the following is added: the amount is unlikely to exceed €50,000 per year.
Small businesses are not entitled to charge VAT to other businesses, nor are they entitled to deduct VAT.
Although they do not have to pay VAT, small businesses are obliged to register with the tax office and make an annual VAT return.
A small entrepreneur may declare the non-application of Paragraph 19 (1) of the German VAT Act.
This declaration shall be binding for the next five years.
It may then charge VAT and deduct VAT.
Non-resident taxable persons may appoint a fiscal representative (§ 22a Ustst).
It is essential that they make exclusively tax-free transactions and refrain from deducting VAT.
The fiscal representative fulfils the tax obligations of the foreign operator and does not have to be registered for VAT purposes.
The invoices shall state that a fiscal representative has been appointed.
Comparison and evaluation
The situation varies from one country to another.
While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the level of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the first requirement for registration (among others) is to exceed the threshold laid down in the VAT Act.
If an entrepreneur does not exceed this threshold, he may be registered on a voluntary basis.
The registration procedure in Germany is standardised, but differences may arise due to different organisational structures in the different Länder.
In the Czech Republic, the taxpayer receives a tax number for any tax at the time of his first registration.
In the case of its registration for VAT, this tax number shall also apply to intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, an entrepreneur registered for VAT purposes receives a tax number exclusively for domestic German transactions.
If the German entrepreneur wants to carry out intra-Community transactions, he must apply specifically for the allocation of a VAT ID number.
Both the Sao and the BRH found that the German two-stage registration system in other Member States, such as the Czech Republic, awarded a single identification number for both the national registration of VAT and intra-Community transactions. may lead to serious misunderstandings.
On the other hand, the two-stage system allows for retroactive (national registration) in cases where the taxable person does not declare his business to the municipality or to the competent Fa.
This retroactive registration makes it possible to apply VAT correctly for previous investment periods, in particular for an accurate estimate of the VAT debt.
As different registration procedures cause problems, the rules should be harmonised for the whole of the EC.
The German Parliament recently decided to introduce a tax identification number.
This is to be allocated by the Federal Tax Office to any natural person after birth.
This number shall apply to natural persons residing in Germany for life.
Where a natural person takes up a business activity, the competent Fa shall apply for a commercial tax identification number which serves as VAT identification number.
There should therefore be no delay in the future between the national registration of a taxable person and the allocation of the VAT ID.
Work on the implementation of an it procedure for the management of numbers has not yet been completed.
Cross-border passenger transport by coach
Legislative provisions in the Czech Republic
Pursuant to Article 70 of Law 235 / 2004, the movement of passengers between Member States and between Member States and third countries in the Czech Republic has been exempt from VAT since 1 May 2004 and is entitled to VAT. movement.
The exemption from VAT shall also apply where the movement is carried out by persons registered in other Member States as taxable persons or by foreigners who are taxable domestically.
The return journey is considered as a separate transport operation.
If non-resident businesses do not carry out any economic activity in the Czech Republic other than the cross-border transport of passengers by coach, they are not obliged to register themselves in the Czech Republic as subject to VAT.
Under the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic, Appendix V, Chapter 5 (1) (b) exempts cross-border passenger transport in the Czech Republic from the VAT obligation.
"For the purposes of the application of Article 28 (3) (b) of Directive 77 / 388 / EEC, the Czech Republic may, in accordance with point 17 of Annex f of the Directive, maintain the exemption for international passenger transport until the conditions laid down in Article 28 (4) of the Directive are fulfilled. the same exemption shall be applied by any of the current Member States or as long as it is applied."
The statutory provisions in Germany
Pursuant to Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006, as implemented in Germany by Paragraph 3b (1) of the UstG, a transport service is carried out where the transport is carried out.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and cross-border passenger transport.
Only the part of the domestic carriage is taxable in Germany.
Nor does German taxation distinguish between resident and non-resident (bus) businesses.
If a non-resident taxable person carries passengers through Germany, the part of the carriage in Germany shall be considered as a taxable carriage.
Prior to the provision of its services in Germany, the non-resident undertaking must notify the competent Fa of its intention to provide passenger transport services.
It registers it for tax purposes (see 4.1.2) and issues a special certificate for each motor coach referred to in the taxpayer's registration.
The trader must indicate his taxable transport services in a German VAT return.
On 1 March 2006, 741 Czech bus operators were registered at Fa Chemnitz-Süd.
If the carriage service is provided to a domestic operator, the non-resident taxpayer does not have to pay the VAT himself to the Fa.
In its place, the domestic customer of services shall pay the VAT to the tax office and the net amount invoiced to the non-resident taxable person, a transaction referred to as a "transfer of tax liability" and complies with Article 196 of the Directive. 2006 / 112 / EC of the Council.
In addition to the notification by a non-resident taxable person and his declaration of income tax, the German financial administration has several means of verifying the accuracy of the tax declaration in respect of passenger transport:
Mobile customs control groups shall check the certificates of buses registered abroad used for the carriage of passengers through Germany.
After each audit, the mobile control groups shall submit an inspection report to the relevant Fa.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group may require the bus driver to pay the VAT before continuing.
The non-resident taxable person may deduct the VAT thus paid from the tax liability indicated in his VAT return.
If the Fa has doubts as to the accuracy of a VAT declaration, it may order an audit to be carried out in the Fa or may use the means of mutual assistance provided for in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 (see point 4.6).
Although the foreign taxpayer refuses to pay the statutory VAT, the Fa may request mutual assistance under Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC.
The BRH considers these means of mutual assistance in tax matters to verify the VAT return or the compliance of a non-resident bus undertaking with the tax obligation to be too burdensome in relation to the low income from the VAT on taxable persons promotions.
In particular, checking the books of a non-resident taxpayer involves disproportionately high costs for the taxpayer himself and for the financial administration.
The latter must examine the foreign books, which requires not only knowledge of the foreign language but also foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, such an examination is likely to involve a higher time burden than that of a resident taxpayer, although the examination is limited to passenger transport operations in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident taxpayer must accept not only the audit rights of his national financial administration, but also those of the other Member States where he carries out passenger transport.
In addition, for each Member State where only one passenger carriage is carried out, the taxpayer must fulfil all existing tax obligations in the different languages and on the basis of the forms of the financial administrations of the relevant EC Member States.. "
This leads to disproportionate administrative burdens for the correct taxation of cross-border passenger transport services.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation varies from one Member State to another.
In the Czech Republic, carriage of passengers between different EC Member States and between Member States and third countries is exempt from VAT under the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the transport service is subject to VAT in accordance with the transport route on the territory of Germany.
If a non-resident taxable person provides such transport services for the first time, he shall first notify the competent Fa.
It registers the taxable person who has to declare the taxable share of the carriage in a tax declaration in Germany.
Enforcement in Germany is very time-consuming.
At least three out of four Czech taxpayers registered at Fa Chemnitz-Süd have the purpose of carrying passengers.
The tax revenue in question is relatively low in relation to the administrative burden.
Member States – which levy VAT pursuant to Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common system of turnover taxes – have a high administrative burden in relation to the relevant tax revenue.
In order to avoid the disproportionate cost of imposing VAT, cross-border passenger transport should be taxable only in one Member State.
This could be the country where the transport starts or where the service provider is established.
Such a type of taxation would require an amendment to Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006.
VAT declarations
Issuing and processing of VAT returns in the Czech Republic
Unless the law provides otherwise, the trader is obliged, even if no tax liability has arisen, to issue a VAT declaration on the form prescribed by the Ministry of Finance within 25 days of the expiry of the tax period.
The tax liability arises with the expiry of the deadline for the submission of the VAT return, with the exception of which, pursuant to Law 235 / 2004, the VAT on the importation of goods is the due date of the tax according to the customs rules.
If, consequently, there is a claim for reimbursement of above-average deductible taxes, this amount shall be reimbursed to the taxpayer within 30 days of the date on which the deduction is fixed without a request being made. needs to become.
The deadline shall not apply in cases where the financial official initiates a tax proceeding concerning the tax liability of the taxable person.
Pursuant to Article 73 (11) of Law No 235 / 2004, the right to deduct may be asserted at the latest with the regular tax return for the last tax period of the calendar year during which the right to deduct has arisen.
After the expiry of this period, the deduction may be applied within three years of the end of the tax period during which the application would have been possible for the first time.
However, this requires the submission of a supplementary VAT return.
A amendment to Law 235 / 2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, allows the submission of a supplementary VAT return only for the period during which the right to deduct could have been claimed for the first time.
A taxpayer must make a supplementary VAT return if: (a) the amount of the corrections leads to an increase in the tax debt, (b) he makes corrections which do not alter the tax debt most recently known in accordance with Article 49 of Law 235 / 2004, it makes corrections to the VAT rate and the tax liability.
A taxpayer may issue a supplementary VAT return if the amount of the corrections reduces the tax liability.
The taxpayer must make the supplementary tax return by the end of the month following the month in which the facts have been established.
The VAT return may be submitted electronically either via the Internet or by means of a data medium.
The levy on the Internet may be carried out with or without a certified electronic signature.
If it is done without an electronic signature, it must also be submitted on disks.
The form for the VAT return contains separate lines for indicating the value of intra-Community supplies and acquisitions.
The value of the services concerned must be indicated in separate rows of the VAT return.
