Issuing and processing of VAT returns in Germany
In Germany, there is a distinction between monthly or quarterly VAT notifications and the annual VAT declaration.
Those taxable persons who are obliged to submit VAT pre-notifications nevertheless have to submit an annual VAT return.
Even small businesses who are not obliged to pay VAT will have to make an annual VAT return.
In principle, taxable persons are required to submit a pre-notification of VAT by the 10th day following the expiry of the calendar quarter in which the VAT is charged (§ 18 (2) of the German VAT Act).
However, where the VAT debt was more than €6,136 in the previous year or is a newly established company, the trader shall be obliged to submit monthly VAT notifications at the latest by the 10th day following the end of the month in question.
The taxable person may also choose to submit monthly VAT notifications if he received a refund of more than €6.136 in the previous year (§ 18 (2a) of the German VAT Act).
If the annual turnover tax does not exceed €512, no VAT advance notifications or VAT returns shall be submitted.
A resulting VAT debt shall be paid 10 days after the end of the tax period.
Reimbursement may lead to a more thorough audit by the financial management.
There are no (statutory) time limits for the processing of VAT returns and for the reimbursement of VAT overpayments.
A guarantee for the amount of the refund may be offered in order to receive a prompt refund.
In principle, VAT returns, including reimbursement cases, must be processed swiftly.
The German VAT Act allows for an extension of these (tax or payment) deadlines (§ 18 (6) of the German VAT Act).
The extension of the deadline must be requested separately.
If it is granted, the VAT pre-notifications and the corresponding payments may be submitted one month later, but in the case of monthly notifications a special advance payment shall be made.
This payment shall be charged against the VAT debt established for the pre-notification period of December.
If an error is detected, the trader must submit a corrected VAT pre-notification.
There is no "additional" VAT return.
Once the VAT return has been submitted to the tax office by 31 May of the following year, the trader may no longer correct an incorrect VAT return but only the incorrect annual VAT return.
Corrections to this VAT return to the taxable person's advantage or disadvantage shall be possible within four years of the end of the year in which the first VAT return was made.
After this four-year period, a VAT return may normally be corrected only in the event of a slight tax cut or tax evasion.
Taxable persons must submit VAT pre-notifications by electronic means.
The Fä may grant derogations from this rule in order to avoid undue hardship.
The annual VAT return may be issued in paper form or via the Internet with or without certification.
If the levy is effected without certification, the taxable person must make the declaration on paper and with his personal signature.
In the absence of VAT prior notifications or declarations, the financial administration is entitled to make a rough estimate of the turnover generated by the taxpayer6.
In the event of late taxation, the taxable person may be subject to a delayed surcharge (up to 10% of the tax debt or up to €25,000).
In a previous examination, the BRH found that the fä often does not raise this delayed surcharge.
In the cases where the delayed surcharges were levied, the amount was fixed in a different and arbitrary manner.
The purpose of the delayed surcharge is therefore not to reduce the average delay, in particular in the submission of the annual VAT return.
The form of the VAT return contains separate lines of information on intra-Community supplies or acquisitions.
There are also separate lines for the supply of services.
Non-taxable transactions shall be indicated in a separate line of the VAT return.
The VAT returns submitted on paper must be either scanned or recorded electronically by personnel specifically designated for that purpose.
The data of electronically submitted tax returns are directly available to the financial administration.
