The Tax Examination and Taxation Methodology Department shall carry out risk analyses, inter alia, in the context of the methodological management of tax audits, sets priorities for the work planning of the financial directorates with regard to the selection of the cases to be examined, establishes risk analyses on the fight against tax evasion and collects in this context information from financial management and other sources and makes proposals for measures to combat tax evasion.
Tax paying agencies exist within the financial directorates, including the search for taxpayers and sectors that are risk-sensitive to the frequency of tax evasion (e.g. internet shops, gold, pharmaceutical industry), the search for non-registered taxpayers (e.g. Internet services, employment services, electronic and print media, etc.), investigation of chain fraud interconnections and information to local financial authorities.
In 12 selected fä, special testing units have been established.
They shall have regional competence and shall carry out tax audits outside the local jurisdiction of the Fä on the basis of the appropriate authorisation.
The need for the establishment of special testing units resulted from the increase in new and "improved" forms of tax evasion identified, particularly in relation to chain transactions.
These special units are considered according to the needs of taxpayers or focused on taxpayers with certain activities, multinationals and taxpayers with particularly high revenues.
The following mechanisms to reduce VAT risks have been integrated into the ATIS system: – the task of “credibility of VAT returns ” to assess the risk-admissibility of tax returns issued, – the task of“ selecting the returns to be verified ” taxable persons ," whereby the taxable persons to be examined are selected on the basis of certain criteria," the task of "mias," which allows financial officials access to the data provided by the other EC Member States.
The “mias ” task allows, inter alia, the following: – verification of the validity of the VAT identification number of taxable persons from other Member States, – confirmation of the value of the goods delivered to a Czech taxable person, such as the VAT number of suppliers of the taxable person concerned from other Member States have been indicated, – establishment of a list of taxable persons who have not submitted a taxable amount, – formal control of the information supplied by taxable persons in the Czech Republic in their taxable amount; before this information is transmitted to other Member States, – establishment of a list of taxable persons whose VAT returns do not conform to the information contained in the MTC on the supply of goods to other Member States, – establishment of a list of taxable persons where the VAT returns do not correspond to the value of the goods acquired from other Member States in the MTC of all their suppliers from other Member States13.
As part of their tasks to combat tax evasion, financial officials have access to data from public authorities such as commercial registers, land register, vehicle register, trade register, etc.
