Although there are joint development working groups, neither the CLO nor the Länder's financial administrations have a completely uniform database.
At the level of the CLO, the St I 2 unit (hereinafter referred to as "Kuss" - the coordinating body for exceptional VAT reviews and tax reviews) collects the assessment of fraud cases in the Opus database.
In cooperation with the countries, a further database called Zauber has been established at the kiss, where financial offices can enter and query the names of discovered missing traders or VAT fraudsters.
The kiss coordinates both related cases of VAT fraud at national level and cases of cross-border VAT fraud.
The experience of the kiss will be brought into the development of the RMS through its participation in the working groups.
Experts from several other organisational units of the CLO and the BMF are also involved.
The formal review of the composition of UStIdNr. of other Member States appearing in the ZM of German taxpayers will be carried out at the CLO.
This formal review will be carried out prior to the transmission of the MZM to other Member States in order to improve the reliability of the MZM data and thus its benefits (see 4.4.2).
The validity of the VAT number mentioned in the MIP will be assessed on the basis of the O _ MCTL calculations submitted by the other Member States (see also 4.4.2 for the procedure for correcting invalid VAT number).
In addition, the RMS of the CLO is based on the mias data transmitted by the other Member States and generates different types of messages to discover suspected missing traders. appearance.
The Länder of the Federal Republic of Germany are required to prepare these communications and have to transmit the outcome of their investigations to the CLO in certain cases.
The fry audit confirmed that all available features need to be included in order to deal with a sufficient likelihood of a case of tax fraud (rather than focusing mainly on a company's turnover).
Accordingly, the BRH recommended that the BMF work on the preparation of the notifications with combinations of different evidence.
The risk management system should also take into account other elements, such as the taxpayer's payment behaviour, the business sector or the company's participation.
A second level of risk management exists with the financial administrations of the Länder and focuses on the processing of VAT pre-notifications and annual declarations.
For example, the system draws up a list of taxable persons who have indicated intra-Community supplies in their VAT advance notification or annual declaration.
This list will be sent to the CLO for the purpose of monitoring the complete delivery of the CMO.
Furthermore, this type of risk management compares the acquisitions indicated by the taxable person in his annual VAT return with the data in the VIES.
The financial administrations of the Länder avoid comparing the quarterly data as they would result in too many inconsistencies due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud, e.g.:
– Supplier and purchaser shall proceed from different times for the implementation of intra-Community transactions;
– Different accounting records and tax declarations of discounts and discounts.
In addition to comparing the figures from the VAT returns with the MiAS data, many Länder have certain risk management mechanisms based on information in the VAT returns and certain other elements (e.g. corporate wording, age of the In). owner / shareholder, number of employees and method of payment of the taxpayer).
Bavaria has introduced a risk management system based on fixed rules, which allows a team of tax fraud specialists (hereinafter referred to as “risk managers ”) to program their own rules in such a way that suspected tax fraudsters are filtered out. will.
This system is used when the VAT notifications are processed by the Fä.
As a result, the competent Fa shall receive the instructions of the RMS before the VAT is fixed.
Since this system is not learnable, risk managers must adapt the rules according to the feedback received from the Fä.
Mecklenburg-Vorpommern has developed an adaptive neural network based on the data of revealed cases of evasion.
On the basis of these data, RMS is able to learn the characteristics of tax evasion.
The system establishes a monthly list of tax cases where evidence of tax evasion is available.
On the basis of this list, the competent fä shall decide on the examination of the taxable persons concerned.
After the audit, the tax auditors must report their results so that the RMS can learn from the results of the tests he has proposed.
In North Rhine-Westphalia an adaptive neural network is used in combination with a rule-based fuzzy system.
Based on many data from processed VAT returns and some other evidence, this neuro-fuzzy system (also known as the datamining system) calculates how likely it is that a taxpayer is involved in tax fraud.
It then draws up a monthly list of suspected tax fraudsters.
On the basis of this list, the taxable persons concerned choose to be audited and report the results of the audit to the data centre concerned.
The introduction of these three RMSs is under way in the Länder.
Since each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three anti-fraud systems appears to be appropriate.
It remains to be seen whether the expected effects will come to an end when actually used.
Comparison and evaluation
Although the present report does not address the specific criteria of RMS in the Czech Republic and Germany, the Sao and the BRH have found that each Member State has developed its own RMS.
Like the different approaches in the three above-mentioned German Länder, the RMS of each European State has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
There is currently an exchange of experience between the financial authorities of the European Member States on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud.
VAT fraud – particularly carousel fraud – has proved to be a problem not a national one, but a European one.
The persons involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one but in several Member States.
A Member State alone cannot develop an effective RMS.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each EC Member State, and if not, fraudsters will seek the Member State with the weakest RMS for their crimes.
The tax losses caused by pan-European VAT fraud do not necessarily affect the Member State in which the initiator is established.
Any other Member State involved in fraud may be affected.
There should therefore be a European exchange of experience on the RMS.
