In the context of the parallel examination, the Sao, in cooperation with the BRH, examined several cases of intra-Community supplies between the Czech Republic and Germany which were not subject to prior exchange of information between the two countries.
The two Courts exchanged information on the cases examined through the CLO of both countries.
21. a Czech company (UCR), which is not based in Germany, informed the relevant Fa (Chemnitz-Süd) that it wanted to operate taxable transactions in Germany.
On the basis of this information, the company was registered as of June 2005 but did not receive a German VAT number.
The (UCR) accepted a contract by a Danish company (UdK) for the production and delivery of wind turbines to Austria on behalf, at the risk and on behalf of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient own production capacity, the Danish company passed a part of the contract to a German taxpayer established in Germany (ude).
The following figure illustrates the contractual relationships and transport routes of wind turbines:
Under German law, the place of performance of these transactions must be determined as described below:
– The Danish company (UdK) sent the wind turbines on its behalf, at its risk and for its own account, for assembly to Austria.
As a result of the assembly, its delivery takes place in Austria, i.e. the supply of wind turbines is taxable in Austria.
– Because the carrier was commissioned by the Danish company (UdK) and the latter had the transport carried out on its own behalf, at its own risk and on its own account, the place of delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE) is where the transport started, i.e. in Germany.
Although wind turbines were delivered to another EC Member State (Au) and the recipient is registered as a taxable person in an EC Member State (CR), no tax exemption could be applied for the delivery of the German subcontractor (UDE). since the EC Member State for which the delivery was intended is different from that of the Czech company19.
Accordingly, the delivery is duly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (UCR) claimed the deduction in its VAT returns.
The place of delivery of the Czech company (UCR) also depends on the place where the transport started.
However, some of the wind turbines were transported from the Czech Republic and others from Germany.
– The supply of wind turbines produced in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
– The supply of the other wind turbines produced in Germany took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) supplied both intra-Community supplies from the Czech Republic to Austria and intra-Community supplies from Germany to Austria.
The BRH found that the Czech company (UCR) had not declared intra-Community supplies either in its German tax returns or in its ZM to the German CLO.
Consequently, the Czech company may have treated all its intra-Community supplies uniformly as intra-Community supplies from the Czech Republic.
The Sao found that (UCR) had not reported intra-Community deliveries to Austria but intra-Community deliveries to Denmark.
In order to ensure the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions in Austria, cooperation between at least four financial administrations (Austrian, Czech, Danish and German) would be necessary, although in this case no indication of tax fraud or tax evasion would be required. available.
In addition, the Sao and the BRH examined case arrangements to indicate the size of the differences caused by the different legislation of 2004 between the figures in the VAT returns and the MiAS data.
The cases examined also show that it takes some time for the taxpayers and the new legislation to apply:
22. in its MZ for the second, third and fourth quarters of 2004, a Czech taxpayer reported goods to a German taxpayer for a total value of CZK 792.977.452.
During the same period, another Czech taxpayer reported intra-Community supplies to another German taxpayer in his MZs for a total value of CZK 18.157.265.
The information transmitted by the BRH to the Sao showed that both were electricity supplies.
Both Czech taxpayers took into account the above-mentioned deliveries under Czech Law 235 / 2004 in force in 2004.
When further examining these transactions, an audit group of the Sao found that in 2004 different legislative provisions on the supply and purchase of electricity between the Czech Republic and Germany were applicable.
While in the Czech Republic taxable persons declared the supply of electricity as intra-Community supplies in accordance with the provisions of Law No 235 / 2004 in force in 2004, the provisions of the German legislation in force in 2004 did not constitute a Community acquisition of goods, but for taxable and taxable transactions in Germany.
The differences in the legislation were eliminated in the Czech Republic by the adoption of Law 635 / 2004, which amended certain tax provisions with effect from 1 January 2005.
23. in the examination of intra-Community supplies and acquisitions in cooperation with the BRH, it was further found that a Czech taxpayer in its Mrs for the first and fourth quarter of 2005 made intra-Community supplies to a German taxpayer. the total value of CZK 240,411,163 and another Czech taxpayer in its MZ declared intra-Community supplies to another German taxpayer for the same period of CZK 263,470,776.
The information transmitted by the BRH to the Sao showed that both were electrical energy supplies.
In accordance with Act No 235 / 2004, which applies from 1 January 2005, in the case of electricity supply, the place of performance of the purchaser is the place where the purchaser is legally established, established or established for which the supply takes place.
Consequently, the Czech taxpayers would not have been allowed to indicate electricity supplies in their MZ for 2005.
The fact that both taxable persons treated the supply of electricity in their MNC as intra-Community supplies resulted in a marginal difference of CZK 503,881,939 in VIES.
Concluding remark
The cooperation achieved the objectives of the BRH and the Sao.
Both Courts gained in-depth knowledge of VAT administration systems in the Czech Republic and Germany.
Cooperation revealed differences in the two systems and in the legislation governing VAT administration.
During the parallel tests, interesting cases of intra-Community supplies or acquisitions were identified.
For some of these, it is worth observing.
On the basis of the results of the audit, both Courts prepared recommendations on the management of VAT.
The follow-up of these recommendations in the form of an audit should be part of the follow-up.
The new experience and knowledge gained through cooperation between the two Courts of Auditors is the basis for the successful conduct of future audits in the field of VAT administration.
